The number of NYC residents&nbsp;treated in an emergency department (ED), including those admitted as inpatients after being seen in an ED,&nbsp;during the months of May-September summed over a 3-year period for the effects of heat and light due to weather conditions or undetermined cause. Residents with a diagnosis of excessive heat due to non-environmental conditions were excluded. Data are based on date of admission and include those who were admitted&nbsp;with a diagnosis of heat-related illness, even if that was not the principal diagnosis.&nbsp;Because ED visits can take place over multiple days, counts are dependent on the date&nbsp;chosen to reference the visit and could differ slightly from those based on date of discharge.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>Notes: The coding system used to represent diagnoses changed in October 2015. Cases admitted before October 1, 2015 are represented by International Classification of Diseases (ICD), 9th Edition, Clinical Modification (ICD-9-CM) codes&nbsp;992.0-992.9, E900.0 or E900.9. Cases admitted on or after October 1, 2015, are represented by the ICD, 10th Edition, Clinical Modification (ICD-10-CM) codes&nbsp;T67, X30, X32.&nbsp; Cases with diagnoses represented by ICD-9-CM code E900.1 (if admitted before October 1, 2015) or ICD-10-CM code W92 (if admitted on or after October 1, 2015) were excluded. Because of the October 1, 2015 change in diagnostic codes from ICD-9-CM to ICD-10-CM, changes in numbers and rates over time should be interpreted with caution because they may be in part due to changes in the coding system.&nbsp;
